Steps to add the latest repository and install the required kernel package:
Check available repositories:
Run the following command to list enabled repositories:

bash
Copy
Edit
yum repolist
Enable the necessary repository:
If you see repositories related to BaseOS or AppStream, ensure they are enabled using:

bash
Copy
Edit
yum-config-manager --enable rhel-8-for-x86_64-baseos-rpms
yum-config-manager --enable rhel-8-for-x86_64-appstream-rpms
Manually add a repository if not available:
If the repository containing the required kernel version is not listed, you may need to manually add it by creating a new repo file:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo vi /etc/yum.repos.d/custom.repo
Add the following content (modify the base URL according to your RHEL version and subscription):

ini
Copy
Edit
[rhel8-latest]
name=RHEL 8 Latest Kernel Repo
baseurl=http://mirror.centos.org/centos/8/BaseOS/x86_64/os/
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release
Clean the yum cache:
After adding the repository, clear and update your cache:

bash
Copy
Edit
yum clean all
yum makecache
Install the desired kernel package:
Now install the required kernel version:

bash
Copy
Edit
yum install kernel-4.18.0-553.33.1.el8_10.x86_64
Verify installation:
Once installed, confirm the kernel version using:

bash
Copy
Edit
rpm -q kernel
If you're using RHEL with a subscription, ensure that your system is registered with Red Hat and can access the appropriate repositories using:

bash
Copy
Edit
subscription-manager register
subscription-manager attach --auto
subscription-manager repos --enable rhel-8-for-x86_64-baseos-rpms
Let me know if you need more help!














